<br>
One of the aspects I find appealing about setting off for the stars is the fact that we would be so far away from Earth and its governments.  Since it would likely be difficult for Earth to regulate interstellar colonies and shape their cultures either intentionally or not, these colonies would likely create a wide ranging diversity of unique cultures and political systems throughout the galaxy.  I believe such an arrangement would ultimately help the evolution of intelligence in the universe. <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>UPS would have trouble making timely deliveries.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
If you could afford the shipping charges. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->    I agree with PO, I don't think faster than light speed is really necessary for us to roam the universe, we just need to get to a good percentage of lightspeed which we know is theoretically attainable right now. <br>
